         <abstract>
            <p>It has been known for some time that solving $x^2 \equiv a (\operatorname{mod} n)$ is as difficult as factoring $n$, at least in the sense that the two problems are random polynomial time equivalent. By contrast, solving a bivariate quadratic congruence $x^2 - ky^2 \equiv m (\operatorname{mod} n)$ can usually be done in random polynomial time even if the factorization of $n$ is unknown. This was first proved by Pollard and Schnorr in 1985 under the assumption of the Piltz conjecture for Dirichlet $L$-functions. We now prove the result without assuming any unproved hypothesis.</p>
          </abstract>
